'l'he simplest explanation seems to be, that there was at any rate a so-called tomb of Archytas on that Matine shore with which Horace from his boyhood would be well acquainted (cf. ‘reference to Venusium 1. 26), and that he makes this the dramatic scene of his ode, which is a monologue, the speaker being the spirit of some traveller who had been shipwrecked on the coast near Archytas' tomb and been left unburied. Ho- race may actually have seen such a case. In this case the argument would r'un thus, the opening reflections being sug- gested by the proximity of the tomb. ‘Yes‚ we must all die! All end at the same goal, though they reach it by different paths, some in war, others by shipwreck.
